In Flutter, you can achieve this by using a `HookWidget` and implementing the `didChangeAppLifecycleState` method. This method is called whenever the app lifecycle changes, such as when a page is shown or navigated to.

Here's an example of how to use `HookWidget` to perform some work when a page is shown:
```dart
import 'package:flutter/widgets/widget.dart';

class MyHookWidget extends HookWidget {
  @override
  Widget build(BuildContext context) {
    return ProviderScope(
      child: Scaffold(
        appBar: AppBar(title: Text('My App')),
        body: Center(child: ElevatedButton(
          child: Text('Click Me'),
          onPressed: () {
            // Perform some work here when the button is pressed
          },
        )),
      ),
    );
  }

  @override
  void didChangeAppLifecycleState(AppLifecycleState state) {
    super.didChangeAppLifecycleState(state);

    if (state == AppLifecycleState.resumed) {
      // Perform some work here when the app resumes, such as initializing variables or fetching data
    }
  }
}
```
In this example, we have defined a `MyHookWidget` that extends `HookWidget`. We have added an `ElevatedButton` to the `body` of the `Scaffold` widget, which is used to trigger some work when it is pressed.

In the `didChangeAppLifecycleState` method, we check the `state` parameter to see if the app has resumed. If so, we can perform some work here, such as initializing variables or fetching data.

Note that this method will also be called when the app is launched, so you may want to add some additional logic to determine whether the work you want to perform should be done in that case.

